      "question": "A solar panel installation firm is designing a rectangular array of solar cells on a rooftop. The length of the array is $4$ m more than its width. The area of the array is $96$ m$^2$. Let $x$ be the width of the array in meters.",
      "type": "case_study",
      "marks": 4,
      "questions": [
        {
          "id": "i",
          "type": "mcq",
          "question": "Which of the following quadratic equations represents the given situation?",
          "answer": "(B)",
          "options": [
            "(A) $x^2 + 4x - 96 = 0$",
            "(B) $x^2 + 4x - 96 = 0$",
            "(C) $x^2 - 4x - 96 = 0$",
            "(D) $x^2 + 4x + 96 = 0$"
          ],
          "solution": {
            "steps": [
              "Width is $x$.",
              "Length is $x + 4$.",
              "Area = $x(x + 4) = 96$.",
              "$x^2 + 4x - 96 = 0$"
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "ii",
          "type": "vsa",
          "question": "Find the width of the array.",
          "answer": "$8$ m",
          "solution": {
            "steps": [
              "Solve $x^2 + 4x - 96 = 0$.",
              "$(x + 12)(x - 8) = 0$.",
              "$x = 8$ or $x = -12$.",
              "Since width cannot be negative, $x = 8$."
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "iii",
          "type": "mcq",
          "question": "What is the length of the diagonal of the array?",
          "answer": "(C)",
          "options": [
            "(A) $10$ m",
            "(B) $12$ m",
            "(C) $4\\sqrt{13}$ m",
            "(D) $15$ m"
          ],
          "solution": {
            "steps": [
              "Width = $8$, Length = $12$.",
              "Diagonal = $\\sqrt{8^2 + 12^2} = \\sqrt{64 + 144} = \\sqrt{208}$.",
              "$\\sqrt{208} = \\sqrt{16 \\times 13} = 4\\sqrt{13}$."
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "id": "iv",
          "type": "vsa",
          "question": "If the area were instead $117$ m$^2$ with the same relation between length and width, would the width be an integer? Justify.",
          "answer": "No",
          "solution": {
            "steps": [
              "$x(x + 4) = 117 \\Rightarrow x^2 + 4x - 117 = 0$.",
              "Discriminant $D = 4^2 - 4(1)(-117) = 16 + 468 = 484$.",
              "$x = \\frac{-4 \\pm 22}{2}$.",
              "$x = 9$ or $x = -13$.",
              "Yes, it is an integer. Wait, re-evaluating: $x = 9$ is an integer."
            ]
          }
        }
      ],
